{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Ammeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the flow of electrical current in a circuit.",
      "anchor": "Think of it like a flow meter on a water pipe measuring how much water passes a point.",
      "misconception": "Believing an ammeter measures electrical pressure rather than flow."
    },
    {
      "term": "Voltmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the electrical potential difference (voltage) between two points.",
      "anchor": "Think of it like a pressure gauge measuring the 'push' in the system.",
      "misconception": "Thinking a voltmeter must be connected in the same way as an ammeter."
    },
    {
      "term": "Ohmmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the electrical resistance of a component or circuit.",
      "anchor": "Used to check if a fuse is blown or a wire is broken by seeing how much it 'resists' flow.",
      "misconception": "Attempting to use an ohmmeter on a live circuit, which can damage the meter."
    },
    {
      "term": "Wattmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the rate at which electrical energy is being used (power).",
      "anchor": "Measures the 'instant' speed of work being done by a load.",
      "misconception": "Confusing the instantaneous power reading with the total energy used over an hour."
    },
    {
      "term": "Energy Meter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument (often called a kWh meter) that measures the total electrical energy consumed over time.",
      "anchor": "The meter found at the intake of a house that determines the electricity bill.",
      "misconception": "Thinking an energy meter and a wattmeter measure the exact same thing."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Ammeters measure current flow.",
    "Voltmeters measure electrical pressure.",
    "Ohmmeters measure resistance to flow.",
    "Wattmeters measure the rate of power.",
    "Energy meters measure total consumption over time."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Using a wattmeter to measure total energy consumption.",
    "Using an ammeter to measure voltage.",
    "Treating 'power' and 'energy' as the same measurement.",
    "Assuming any meter can measure any quantity without changing settings."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "202-2b-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Measuring Current, Voltage, and Resistance",
      "objective": "Identify the specific instruments used to measure current, voltage, and resistance.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To work safely and accurately on an electrical installation, you must select the correct instrument for the specific quantity you are testing. When you need to measure the flow of electrical current, you use an Ammeter. Think of this like a flow meter on a water pipe; it tells you how much electricity is passing through a point in the circuit.",
        "If you need to measure the electrical 'pressure' or potential difference between two points, you use a Voltmeter. This is similar to a pressure gauge in a plumbing system, measuring the force available to push the current. To check how much a component resists that flow—for example, to see if a fuse is blown or a wire is intact—you use an Ohmmeter. This measures electrical resistance.",
        "It is vital to remember that these instruments are not interchangeable. You cannot use a voltmeter to measure current flow directly, and using an ohmmeter on a live circuit can damage the meter. Each tool has a specific job: ammeters for flow, voltmeters for pressure, and ohmmeters for resistance."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about whether you are measuring the flow (current), the pressure (voltage), or the opposition to that flow (resistance)."
    },
    {
      "key": "202-2b-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Measuring Power and Energy",
      "objective": "Identify the specific instruments used to measure electrical power and energy consumption.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "While current and voltage tell us about the circuit's state, we use different tools to measure how much work is being done. To measure Power, which is the instantaneous rate at which electrical energy is being used, we use a Wattmeter. This gives you a 'snapshot' of the load at that exact moment, showing how hard the system is working right now.",
        "However, if we need to know the total amount of electricity consumed over a period of time—the figure used for billing—we use an Energy Meter, often called a kWh meter. You will find these at the intake of every domestic property to record usage over days or months. ",
        "A common mistake is treating 'power' and 'energy' as the same thing. A wattmeter measures the rate of work, whereas an energy meter records the total work done over time. Just as you wouldn't use a speedometer to measure the total distance a car has traveled, you don't use a wattmeter to measure total energy consumption. You must select the Energy Meter for total usage and the Wattmeter for the instantaneous power rate."
      ],
      "hint": "Consider if you need to know how much power is being used 'right now' or how much has been used 'in total' over time."
    }
  ]
}

