          "answerGuidance": [
            "Voltmeter",
            "A voltmeter"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What instrument is used to measure the electrical resistance of a component like a fuse?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Ohmmeter",
            "An ohmmeter"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why is it technically incorrect to use a voltmeter when you need to check if a wire is physically broken or a fuse is blown?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "A voltmeter measures electrical pressure between points",
        "An ohmmeter is required to measure the resistance of the component",
        "Checking for a break requires measuring the opposition to flow",
        "The instruments have different specific jobs and are not interchangeable"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about whether you are measuring the flow (current), the pressure (voltage), or the opposition to that flow (resistance)."
    },
    {
      "title": "Measuring Power and Energy",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "Which instrument is used to measure the instantaneous rate at which electrical energy is being used?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Wattmeter",
            "A wattmeter"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the name of the instrument used to measure the total electrical energy consumed over a period of time?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Energy Meter",
            "An energy meter"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the common technical name for an energy meter, often found at a domestic property intake?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "kWh meter",
            "Kilowatt-hour meter"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "If a customer wants to know their total electricity cost for the month, why would a wattmeter be the wrong tool for the job?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "A wattmeter only provides a snapshot of the power rate at one moment",
        "Billing requires the total consumption over time",
        "Energy meters record usage over days or months whereas wattmeters show instantaneous load",
        "The wattmeter does not track the total work done over a duration"
      ],
      "hint": "Consider if you need to know how much power is being used 'right now' or how much has been used 'in total' over time."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "guidedPractice": {
    "title": "Guided Practice: Measuring Circuit Flow",
    "objective": "Guide the learner through selecting the correct meter for a practical scenario involving current flow, mirroring the worked example's selection process.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Scenario: You are investigating a circuit where a lamp is appearing dim. You need to measure the flow of electricity through the conductor to see if it matches the lamp's rated current.",
      "Step 1: Identify the quantity. You are measuring the 'flow' of electricity, which is current.",
      "Step 2: Match the instrument to the quantity. Just as the worked example used an Ohmmeter for resistance, you must select the tool for current."
    ],
    "questionText": "Based on the scenario above, which specific instrument must you use to measure the flow of electrical current in the circuit?",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Ammeter"
    ],
    "hint": "Think of the tool that acts like a flow meter on a water pipe."
  },
  "practice": {
    "title": "Independent Practice: Monitoring Consumption",
    "objective": "Assess the learner's ability to identify the correct instrument for measuring total energy consumption over time.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "A factory manager wants to record the total amount of electricity used by a production line over a full 24-hour shift to calculate the daily running costs.",
      "This task requires measuring the total electrical energy consumed over a period of time, rather than the instantaneous power or the electrical pressure."
    ],
    "questionText": "Identify the specific instrument required to measure this total electrical energy consumption for billing purposes.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Energy meter",
      "kWh meter",
      "Kilowatt-hour meter"
    ],
    "hint": "This is the meter you would typically find at the intake of a domestic or commercial property to track usage over time."
  }
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Power vs. Energy Monitoring",
    "objective": "Evaluate the learner's ability to distinguish between instantaneous power measurement and long-term energy consumption monitoring in a practical site survey.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "When conducting a site survey for a large electrical installation, you often need to look at two different aspects of the load. First, you need to know the 'instantaneous' demand to ensure the cables and switchgear are sized correctly for the current 'push' and 'flow'.",
      "Second, the client will want to know the total consumption over a specific billing period to forecast their running costs. Using the wrong tool here would result in either a snapshot that misses the big picture or a total figure that doesn't show the peak demand."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are monitoring a new industrial heater. You need to measure the rate at which it is using power 'right now' to check for overloading, and also record the total electrical energy it consumes over a full week for the accounts department. Name the two specific instruments required for these tasks and explain the fundamental difference in what they measure.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Wattmeter: Measures the instantaneous rate of power (how hard the system is working at that moment).",
      "Energy Meter (or kWh meter): Measures the total electrical energy consumed over a period of time (for billing/usage tracking).",
      "The fundamental difference is that one measures a 'snapshot' rate (Power) while the other records 'accumulated' work (Energy)."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which tool acts like a speedometer (rate) and which acts like an odometer (total distance)."
  }
}

